  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This 2025 dataset from Utrecht University, deposited on the NCCR MARVEL Materials Cloud platform, supports experimental and computational research into one-dimensional Yu-Shiba-Rusinov (YSR) states localized at the edges of ferromagnetic CrCl\u2083 monolayers placed on the superconductor NbSe\u2082. Although newly released and not yet formally cited, it has already accumulated ten online mentions and demonstrates clear downstream reuse through seven documented connections to related publications and software resources.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset is the work of six researchers at Utrecht University \u2014 Jan P. Cuperus, Arnold H. Kole, Andr\u00e9s R. Botello-M\u00e9ndez, Zeila Zanolli, Daniel Vanmaekelbergh, and Ingmar Swart \u2014 representing a collaboration that spans experimental scanning tunneling microscopy and spectroscopy with first-principles computational modeling. The subject matter sits at the frontier of condensed matter physics, targeting the interplay between ferromagnetism and superconductivity in a van der Waals heterojunction: a CrCl\u2083 monolayer on a NbSe\u2082 substrate. YSR states, which arise when magnetic impurities are coupled to a superconductor, are of particular interest as candidate platforms for topological quantum information, making the precise spatial characterization offered here scientifically timely.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset supplements a primary journal article published in npj Quantum Materials and is formally linked, via DataCite metadata, to a rich ecosystem of methodological foundations \u2014 including the SIESTA density-functional code, the TB2J exchange-coupling toolkit, the AiiDA-SIESTA workflow plugin, and several foundational computational-methods papers. This web of declared dependencies signals a computationally intensive study in which reproducibility was taken seriously: users wishing to reuse the data have clear pathways to the software environment that generated it. The reuse graph records seven downstream connections in total, spanning an associated dataset record, an indexed journal article mention, and multiple supporting methodological references.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Early dissemination signals are modest but present. Ten online mentions have been tracked across monitored channels, consistent with the dataset's very recent release and the specialist nature of the underlying physics. No formal citations have yet been recorded in scholarly databases, which is entirely expected at this stage. The Stack Overflow discussions appearing in the public discourse log bear no evident subject-matter connection to condensed matter physics and most likely reflect noise in the automated monitoring pipeline rather than genuine engagement with this work.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, this deposit exemplifies best practices in open research data for the physical sciences: it carries a clear green open-access status, is hosted on a domain-specific trusted repository, and is tightly linked to both the peer-reviewed publication it supports and the computational tools required to reproduce its results. Its scientific value lies in providing the community with direct evidence \u2014 from scanning tunneling microscopy and spectroscopy \u2014 that YSR states in this system are genuinely one-dimensional and edge-localized, a finding with implications for the design of topologically non-trivial phases in two-dimensional magnetic\u2013superconductor heterostructures. Uptake and formal citation activity can reasonably be expected to grow as the companion article circulates within the condensed matter community.</p>",
